<font color="#FF0000">VIETNAM II</font><br>
<tt>Tue Sep  2 13:59:11 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
<br>
To Tom, Wingmen<br><br>
You and others have done here what the world has done to princess Di's murderer. You blame the photographers that chased her vehicle, (the Press that fed our 6:00 news programs during the war.) the world now, blames the driver who appeared to have been intoxicated (Our government that did not know what they were doing and what they were doing was doing it all wrong). But who's to blame. Was it The playboy out to conquer one more damsel. An individual who would take advantage of her sweetness and innocence and needs, certainly one who loved another would not have risked the danger he placed her in, by trying to outrun the press and government control. Ho chi Mien was just like that playboy who didn't care enough about his homeland that he traded her in for his own selfish needs. <br>
That's what happened with Nam, we consentrated on the governments and not on the reason China wanted Vietnam, was it love or to spend another night with a a different women? that caused him to disregard her safety? That's what Ho Chi Mihn did when he embraced China, in order to gain South Vietnam. <br><br>
 You say you loved and admired the Vietnamese people yet you were not willing to help them obtain the same democratic liberties we enjoyed. Help them to become free from Communist aggression, I volunteered to go there and knew why. I killed the enemy because they were the enemy, not just, because someone told me to. That's wrong if you killed without reason  that's worst then popping off some caps at individuals still out in the field past curfew. That type of reason, to kill and not know why I can not understand. <br>
What I saw in Vietnam was injustice and throughout God's book, he has never tolerated injustice. God has never turned the other cheek on the wickedness of the world, on sin, murder and aggressive domination and when nations enslave other nations. Oh! They get away with it for awhile especially when other nations stand idle and dare not interfere because its across the sea, but then we pay the price sooner or later. For us to know what we should have done and don't do it that's wrong and this nation is today being held accountable for those cowardly acts.  Because we did not follow through. <br><br>
I did not understand the politics of the war, who did at that time. But I understood what I saw, I understood  the hunger I saw in the Vietnamese kids who jumped onto the garbage truck to gain what morsals of food they could for survival. I understood the maimed and the suffering I saw. I only wished I could have done more for them. <br>
Had my nation not gone to war, I would have wanted to go there and help them fight the communist terrorist that plundered, raped, killed innocent men, women and children.<br>
That is what I saw that is what I fought for, Not for Johnson or what you and others believed back home. Passive gutless invdividuals that were so easily swayed by communist propaganda back home that I could understand, could not comprehand, where did all the brave men at home went to, why did they remain silent. Where was wisdom and common sense?  When I went to Nam, America was supportive of us, when Marty came honme on R&amp;R he said that people were beginning to demonstrate against the war, but he also said that many Americans were staging counter-demonstration rallies in support of us. What happened? We lost that war and that influenced the out come in Nam after my tour ended. <br>
I have no pain from my tour of duty in Vietnam, I lost many friends there and that is a land of honor not pain to me. Those men did not die in vain as you and spatz believe and indicate through your postings. <br>
Perhaps I am violating the spirit of this thread, but if what you say is true you were no combat warrior and now I can understand why you feel like you do. I would also feel that way.  I wouldn't be speaking here, I would still be hiding from the shame and guilt. you were there but your heart was not.<br>
I fought a war with honor, guts and yes, even glory. But I did not seek glory, the honor others have paid me by saying Cook thanks for being there, Cook if you hadn't opened up I wouldn't be here today. Cook when your gun talked I knew, I knew things were going to be alright.I can't count the Marines and the Vietnamese who have shook my hand and you know what?  I found it an honor. To have been able to help them, I never  sought the medals or the glory I saw injustice and reacted. I have no regrets for that, I suffer no shame, there is no dishonor in that. It was a right war at the right time, but there were no generals and politicans that cared for all the right reasons. But that does not make the war wrong.<br>
Yes I blame those who protested our involvement in Nam. I believed they helped prolong the war and as a result more Americans died because of the unrest and choas they caused at home. Because of the confusion and doult they caused, because of the pain they caused upon those who did serve with honor. <br>
Do you know what's wrong we looked at all the wrong places to place the blame upon. Sure we could have handled it differently., we could have made friends with Ho Chi Minh right from the start and that would have won Vietnam easily. He wanted that. But when politics changed, when the Chinese government promised Ho chi arms, weapons, supplies and men little ho chi did what other have done through the ages he turned traitor he let a revolutionary war against his own people at the expense of Vietnam becoming a communist state, he joined China who had been Vietnam's enemy for decades. But I didn't know that then. I only knew we were fighting communist aggression in Southeast asia and that history has proven to be true.<br>
The problem is for you to call them gooks would be wrong you saw them not as the enemy, I called them gooks after they became my enemy. I did not dehumanize them before., they did that, that is why I find no faultt in calling anyone a gook that I was about to kill for all the right reasons.<br>

<p><code>-- cookbarela@iname.com  (Sparrowhawk) </code><p>


